.TH SHOREWALL-NFT-RULES 5 "2026-04-24" "shorewall-nft 1.10.2" "File Formats"
.SH NAME
shorewall\-nft\-rules \- firewall rules for shorewall-nft
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.I rules
file is the primary place where you allow or deny specific traffic between
zones.  Rules are checked before the default policy defined in
.IR shorewall\-nft\-policy (5).

The compiler reads this file during the IR-construction pass and emits one
or more nft rules per row into the appropriate zone-pair chain.

The
.I rules
file supports
.B ?SECTION
blocks:
.B ?SECTION NEW
(default),
.BR "?SECTION ESTABLISHED" ,
.BR "?SECTION RELATED" ,
.BR "?SECTION INVALID" ,
.BR "?SECTION UNTRACKED" .
Most operators keep all rules in the
.B NEW
section.

.SH FILE FORMAT
Location:
.I /etc/shorewall/rules
(or inside a merged
.IR /etc/shorewall46/ ).
.PP
Columns are whitespace-separated.  Lines beginning with
.B #
are comments.  Long lines may be continued with a trailing backslash.

.TS
l l l.
Column	Required	Description
_
ACTION	yes	What to do (ACCEPT, DROP, REJECT, DNAT, …)
SOURCE	yes	Source zone or address
DEST	yes	Destination zone or address
PROTO	no	Protocol number or name (tcp, udp, icmp, …)
DPORT	no	Destination port(s) or range
SPORT	no	Source port(s) or range
ORIG_DEST	no	Original destination for DNAT rules
RATE	no	Rate limit: \fIN/unit\fB:\fIburst\fR or \fBLIMIT:\fIname,rate,burst\fR
USER	no	User/group match
MARK	no	Connection mark
CONNLIMIT	no	Max concurrent connections from source: \fIcount\fR[:\fImask\fR]
TIME	no	Time range match
HEADERS	no	IPv6 header match
SWITCH	no	Runtime switch name
HELPER	no	conntrack helper name
.TE

.SS ACTION syntax
.TP
.B ACCEPT
Pass the packet.
.TP
.B DROP
Silently discard.
.TP
.B REJECT
Discard and notify sender.
.TP
.B DNAT[\fI:addr\fR][\fI:port\fR]
Destination NAT.  Translates the destination to
.IR addr : port .
.TP
.B SNAT[\fI:addr\fR]
Source NAT.
.TP
.B LOG[\fI:level\fR][\fI:prefix\fR]
Log and continue.
.TP
.BI Macro / name
Built-in macro (e.g.
.BR SSH ,
.BR HTTP ,
.BR HTTPS )
or action file.

.SS SOURCE / DEST syntax
.TP
.I zone
Zone name (matches all hosts in that zone).
.TP
.IB zone : address
Zone restricted to a specific address or CIDR prefix.
.TP
.IB zone : dnst: hostname
Zone with a DNS-driven nft set for
.I hostname
(populated by shorewalld via the tap pipeline).
Preferred form; see
.B dns:
below.
.TP
.IB zone : dns: hostname
Deprecated alias for
.BR dnst: hostname .
Both tokens produce identical IR output.  Emits a compile-time warning
— migrate to
.BR dnst: .
.TP
.IB zone : dnsr: hostname
Like
.B dnst:
but uses the active pull resolver backend in shorewalld.
.TP
.IB zone : nfset: name
Reference a named set declared in
.IR shorewall\-nft\-nfsets (5).
.TP
.IB zone :! nfset: name
Negated nfset reference — match packets whose address is
.I not
in the set.
.TP
.IB + setname
Classic Shorewall ipset reference.
The set must be declared via a load-sets directive or
.IR shorewall\-nft\-nfsets (5).
The column position determines whether
.I saddr
or
.I daddr
is matched (source column →
.BR saddr ;
dest column →
.BR daddr ).
.TP
.IB + setname [ src | dst | src,dst ]
Bracket flags override the column-position default.
.B src
forces source-address matching,
.B dst
forces destination-address matching,
.B src,dst
emits two sub-matches (both saddr and daddr must be in the set).
.TP
.IB +[ set1 , set2 , set3 ]
AND-multi-set: the packet must match
.I all
listed sets simultaneously.
Without bracket flags the column side applies to every member.
Negated form
.BI !+[ set1 , set2 ]
matches if at least one set does
.I not
contain the address.
.TP
.B $FW
Shorthand for the firewall zone.
.TP
.B all
Match any zone.
.TP
.BI ! address
Negated address.

.SS RATE column
.TP
.IB N / unit : burst
Simple token-bucket rate limit applied per rule.
.I unit
is
.BR second ,
.BR minute ,
.BR hour ,
or
.BR day .
.I burst
is the maximum burst above the steady rate.  Example:
.BR 10/minute:5 .
.TP
.BI LIMIT: name , rate , burst
Named per-source hashlimit (nft
.BR meter ).
.I name
is the meter table name; useful for sharing a limit across multiple rules.

.SS CONNLIMIT column
.TP
.IB count [: mask ]
Limit simultaneous connections from a single source (or subnet when
.I mask
is given as an IPv4 prefix length).  Example:
.B 10
limits 10 connections per source IP;
.B 50:24
limits 50 connections per source /24.

.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Basic service access rules:
.RS
.nf
#ACTION  SOURCE  DEST    PROTO   DPORT
ACCEPT   loc     fw      tcp     22
ACCEPT   loc     net     tcp     80,443
ACCEPT   fw      net     tcp     80,443,587
.fi
.RE
.PP
DNAT for inbound web traffic to a DMZ host:
.RS
.nf
DNAT     net     dmz:198.51.100.10   tcp  80
DNAT     net     dmz:198.51.100.10   tcp  443
.fi
.RE
.PP
DNS-driven rule — allow outbound to github.com only:
.RS
.nf
ACCEPT   loc     net:dns:github.com  tcp  443
.fi
.RE
.PP
Rate-limited SSH to prevent brute-force:
.RS
.nf
ACCEPT   net     fw      tcp     22      -   -  3/min:5
.fi
.RE
.PP
Named nfset reference for a CDN allowlist:
.RS
.nf
ACCEPT   net:nfset:allowlist  loc
.fi
.RE
.PP
DNS-driven rule using the preferred
.B dnst:
prefix:
.RS
.nf
ACCEPT   loc     net:dnst:api.example.com   tcp  443
.fi
.RE
.PP
Classic ipset with bracket flag — match destination address against a
blocklist regardless of which column carries the set reference:
.RS
.nf
DROP     +blocklist[src]   fw
DROP     fw                +blocklist[dst]
.fi
.RE
.PP
AND-multi-set — packet must be in both sets simultaneously:
.RS
.nf
ACCEPT   +[trusted,vpn-users]   fw   tcp   22
.fi
.RE

